Find the integer $n,$ $-90 < n < 90,$ such that $\tan n^\circ = \tan 252^\circ.$
inference:
Since $\tan (180^\circ + \theta) = \tan \theta,$ we have

$$\tan n^\circ = \tan 252^\circ = \tan (252^\circ - 180^\circ) = \tan 72^\circ.$$

Since $72^\circ$ is in the first quadrant, $n^\circ$ must also be in the first quadrant. Therefore, $n$ is the integer such that $0^\circ < n^\circ < 90^\circ$ and $\tan n^\circ = \tan 72^\circ.$

Since $\tan 72^\circ \approx 3.0777,$ we have $n \approx 72^\circ.$

The integer $n$ such that $-90^\circ < n < 90^\circ$ and $\tan n^\circ = \tan 252^\circ$ is $\boxed{72}.$

Final Answer: $\boxed{72}.$ I hope it is correct.
